 C compilers replace the #defines into the code at compile time, so 
they do not need to store a value, just a note that the constant has 
been defined. With conversion to Blitz you will need to do something 
clever as if you take a constant as being defined at -1 and not at 0, 
what happens when someone defines a constant to have a value at 0? 
Maybe you need to create another constant which shows if the constant 
has been defined, i.e. in C:

#define BLAHBLAH

